{
  "text": "Pooled data from three studies indicated that the self-esteem score was higher in the intervention group (I 2 =0%, P=0.02, 95% CI: 0.18, 2.22), measured by the Rosenberg Self-Esteem Scale (Table 3) . [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] Meanwhile, exercise intervention reduced depression (I 2 =2%, P=0.001, 95% CI: -3.36, -0.80, Figure 3 ) and anxiety score (I 2 =0%, P0.0001, 95% CI: -4.76, -1.58, Figure 3 ), which were of clinical importance. However, the pooled results showed no difference in happiness and stress between intervention and control groups, assessed by the 2-item Fordyce Happiness Measure and the Perceived Stress Scale (Table 3) .",
